{"term":"1960","caseName":"Michigan National Bank v. Michigan","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1960/155","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 18, 1961","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren7/oral_argument_audio/14024","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 155, Michigan National Bank et al., Appellants, versus Michigan et al.","start":0,"stop":8.428,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Mr. Klein.","start":8.428,"stop":9.974,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":9.974,"stop":16.605,"duration":6.63},{"text":"This is an appeal from a judgment of the Michigan Supreme Court.","start":16.605,"stop":24.981,"duration":8.38},{"text":"The basic question in this case is whether or not, the National Bank Tax Act known as Revised Statute 5219 was violated by the State of Michigan under Act 9 of the Public Acts of 1953, taxing shares of national banks at a rate 13 times greater than the state taxes shares of savings and loan associations.","start":24.981,"stop":77.261,"duration":52.28},{"text":"Now, although Act 9 was enacted in 1953, it relates back to the 1952 taxes.","start":77.261,"stop":88.802,"duration":11.54},{"text":"There had been a tax in effect, the appellant paid that tax some $18,000 and then this Act 9 of 1953 also imposed this new tax of $5.5 per thousand of paid up capital surplus and undivided profits has contrasted with a tax of only 40 cents a thousand on shares of savings and loan associations.","start":88.802,"stop":125.751,"duration":36.95},{"text":"The appellant paid the tax, the additional $49,000 tax under protest took the proper procedure, tried it in front of the Court of Claims in Michigan, then to the Supreme Court and we are now here.","start":125.751,"stop":142.052,"duration":16.3},{"text":"There are other taxes from 1953 to 1959 or 1960 the date in which there are cases pending awaiting the determination of this case.","start":142.052,"stop":156.42,"duration":14.37},{"text":"Before giving even a preliminary outline, I want to point out one thing to the Court that this is not a case of tax immunity or tax avoidance.","start":156.42,"stop":169.961,"duration":13.54},{"text":"This is a tax -- this is a case in which the appellant urges on this Court that under the federal statute, national banks are entitled to be taxed equally but at no greater rate than other moneyed capital which comes into competition with the business of the national banks.","start":169.961,"stop":197.551,"duration":27.59},{"text":"And we say in this case, if that injunction of the federal statute were observed, the State of Michigan would collect additional taxes from savings and loan associations shareholders in the annual amount of $8,000,000 a year.","start":197.551,"stop":219.346,"duration":21.8},{"text":"Now preliminarily, I'd like to point out to the Court that we submit that savings and loan associations are the dominant and principle competitors of national banks in the residential mortgage loan business, that that business is a substantial business.","start":219.346,"stop":249.312,"duration":29.97},{"text":"In the year in question, it was over -- over a half of billion dollars was employed in the State of Michigan by savings and loan in their business, the day over a billion and a half dollars and that type of business, your residential mortgage loan business, is a vital, essential, substantial, important phase of the business of national banks.","start":249.312,"stop":277.26,"duration":27.95},{"text":"In the case of appellant, that residential mortgage loan business amounted to 40% of appellants' total loans, three times more than its commercial loans accounted for 32% of its total income and constituted over 20% of its gross assets.","start":277.26,"stop":302.296,"duration":25.04},{"text":"I gave to that in a preliminary way only.","start":302.296,"stop":304.746,"duration":2.45},{"text":"We'll get into the details.","start":304.746,"stop":307.006,"duration":2.26},{"text":"So, the Court has the proper background.","start":307.006,"stop":310.639,"duration":3.63},{"text":"I should like to point out that in the year 1952 which is the year which -- which we're here concerned, there were 77 national banks operating in the State of Michigan and there were 67 savings and loan associations, about half were domestic Michigan saving and loan associations and the other half federal savings and loan associations.","start":310.639,"stop":342.707,"duration":32.07},{"text":"The Appellant Bank is a national bank which operates in seven cities throughout the State.","start":342.707,"stop":353.349,"duration":10.64},{"text":"They are not large metropolitan cities like Detroit where commercial loans are of greater importance than they are to the out state bank mortgage loans, residential mortgage loans are very important in fact, the most important, I would say operation of the out state national banks.","start":353.349,"stop":380.263,"duration":26.91},{"text":"The Appellant operates in cities like Battle Creek, Michigan population 48,000, Port Huron population 35,000, Lansing 92,000, Saginaw 92,000, Flint 163,000, Grand Rapids 176,000 and then one small community of Marshall 5700.","start":380.263,"stop":407.324,"duration":27.06},{"text":"But they're all medium, small medium modern size cities not comparable to the big city banks although the city banks are now more and more engaged in the residential mortgage.","start":407.324,"stop":424.631,"duration":17.31},{"text":"Now, with that background, we come to the power of the state to tax.","start":424.631,"stop":433.379,"duration":8.75},{"text":"I believe this Court has clearly stated that absent congressional grant of authority of the State, no State has the power to tax national banks or their shares at all, because national banks are governmental agencies instrumentalities actually performing in many respects.","start":433.379,"stop":469.067,"duration":35.69},{"text":"The basic physical policies of the United States Government, and this Court has therefore held that because national banks perform that essential government function, the State of Michigan, no State absent congressional authority would have power to tax either national banks or their shares at all, and you so held in two cases cited in our brief.","start":469.067,"stop":502.245,"duration":33.18},{"text":"However --","start":502.245,"stop":502.948,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"One of these banks in the Jackson, Michigan?","start":502.948,"stop":505.034,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"No sir, but one of -- there are five intervening banks sir and one of Jackson Banks did intervene the -- the National Bank of Jackson intervened sir.","start":505.034,"stop":519.876,"duration":14.84},{"text":"The -- in the case of the intervenors was held in advance because the time consumed in preparing this voluminous record and the burden upon us was so great that we elected to defer trial of the intervening cases until the disposition of this case.","start":519.876,"stop":540.612,"duration":20.74},{"text":"Now, Congress did authorize and empower states to tax originally in 1864, to tax only shares of national banks and that wasn't broadened until 1923 when there were two other methods of taxation permitted the tax on the dividens from shares and also in income tax on the bank itself as contrasted with shares.","start":540.612,"stop":575.182,"duration":34.57},{"text":"And in 1926, there was authorized.","start":575.182,"stop":579.235,"duration":4.05},{"text":"States were permitted to impose a franchise tax measured by income.","start":579.235,"stop":584.488,"duration":5.25},{"text":"But Congress provided that when a State, elected one method of taxation, that method was in lieu of all others, it could not employ both methods at the same time.","start":584.488,"stop":601.428,"duration":16.94},{"text":"In this case, Act 9, I'll call it Act 9 of Michigan, imposed a tax on shares.","start":601.428,"stop":612.107,"duration":10.68},{"text":"It is a share tax just as the original Act permitted to be imposed, on shares of national banks which it imposed upon the bank which in turn could or could not pay it for its shareholders but the assessment was made and is made on the banks.","start":612.107,"stop":638.241,"duration":26.13},{"text":"Now, Section R.S. Section Revised Statute 5219, the tax on shares, the empowering of a State to tax on shares, specifically provide Section 1 (b) that such tax by a State and I quote, \"shall not be at a greater rate, than as assessed upon other moneyed capital in the hands of individual citizens of such State coming into competition with the business of national banks.\"","start":638.241,"stop":682.455,"duration":44.21},{"text":"Now, this Court has held that a State so empowered to tax, national bank shares may only do it in the manner and through the extent and subject to the expressed limitations provided by Congress in this R.S. 5219.","start":682.455,"stop":706.476,"duration":24.02},{"text":"One, the injunction is that the tax shall not be at a greater rate than it's assessed upon other moneyed capital.","start":706.476,"stop":714.997,"duration":8.52},{"text":"The other moneyed capital must come in the competition with the substantial phase of the business of the national bank.","start":714.997,"stop":723.336,"duration":8.34},{"text":"And three, such competition when compare is substantial when compared to the total capitalization of national banks in the State.","start":723.336,"stop":733.984,"duration":10.65},{"text":"In this case, it's three times the total capitalization.","start":733.984,"stop":741.18,"duration":7.2},{"text":"Now, looking at this empowering statute of Congress, we first determined what is meant by other moneyed capital.","start":741.18,"stop":752.616,"duration":11.44},{"text":"Originally, when this Act was passed other moneyed capital meant any kind, all kinds of intangible personal property, stocks, bond, judgments, anything, coming in the competition was not in the statute and it wasn't a requirement.","start":752.616,"stop":773.292,"duration":20.68},{"text":"But in 1887, this Court redefined moneyed capital in the Mercantile case, and it said, and this becomes important, and I quote, \"That moneyed capital include shares of stock or other interests owned by individuals in all enterprises in which the capital employed in carrying on its business is money where the object of the business is the making of profit by its use as money reduced again to money and reinvested.\"","start":773.292,"stop":822.086,"duration":48.79},{"text":"In other words, moneyed capital means that its money either employed by an individual, in an individual capacity partnership by investing in shares and that business employing it in a business where the inventory so to speak is money, money is loaned out and money is the business carried out and it's a business of money.","start":822.086,"stop":851.817,"duration":29.73},{"text":"And we submit, and we'll get into this more in detail, that shares in a savings and loan associations are moneyed capital.","start":851.817,"stop":863.098,"duration":11.28},{"text":"In other words, an individual buy some shares.","start":863.098,"stop":869.41,"duration":6.31},{"text":"Those shares are employed by a corporation, whose business is money, loaning out the money primarily on real estate residential mortgages.","start":869.41,"stop":883.463,"duration":14.05},{"text":"So we say, initially and we'll get more into detail on that, that investment in shares in savings and loan association is other moneyed capital because its business is money, the loaning of money.","start":883.463,"stop":898.809,"duration":15.35}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there -- is there any dispute between you on that issue?","start":898.809,"stop":901.859,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there wasn't up until through the Supreme Court, sir.","start":901.859,"stop":906.045,"duration":4.19},{"text":"I think the Supreme Court of Michigan assumed it was moneyed capital but I do believe at this point the appellee questions asked, and we will discuss that because we will -- if you wish I will answer it now appropriately.","start":906.045,"stop":921.148,"duration":15.1},{"text":"Up through the Supreme Court of Michigan including its opinion, I believe it was assumed that it was other moneyed capital.","start":921.148,"stop":931.318,"duration":10.17},{"text":"And that other moneyed capital did not have to be in stock.","start":931.318,"stop":934.94,"duration":3.62},{"text":"It could be an individual.","start":934.94,"stop":936.471,"duration":1.53},{"text":"I could go in the real estate mortgage business and put a certain amount of money in it, loan it out on residential mortgages, get paid back and loan some more out, and then if l think I had too much in the business, I could retire that and keep a lesser amount of this.","start":936.471,"stop":954.49,"duration":18.02},{"text":"Now, the second part of the statute, the question of coming into competition, it must be moneyed capital, coming into competition with the substantial phase of the business of national banks.","start":954.49,"stop":970.048,"duration":15.56},{"text":"Originally, as up till Mercantile, the moneyed capital did not have to come into competition with the business of national banks.","start":970.048,"stop":981.626,"duration":11.58},{"text":"It was all kinds of intangible money.","start":981.626,"stop":984.808,"duration":3.18},{"text":"Then in Mercantile, the Court -- this Court said, it had to come into competition and there was lot of backing and filling and finally in 1923 Congress codified that determination of this Court into the statute and provided that it had to be not only other moneyed capital, but it had to come into competition with the business of national banks.","start":984.808,"stop":1012.531,"duration":27.72},{"text":"And this Court has go on further that it had to be substantial in amount, and that it had to come into competition with the substantial phase of the business of national banks.","start":1012.531,"stop":1028.059,"duration":15.53},{"text":"I, again, will come back to the history.","start":1028.059,"stop":1031.058,"duration":3},{"text":"Now, what are the facts in this case?","start":1031.058,"stop":1035.667,"duration":4.61},{"text":"Today, in 1952, these savings and loan associations in Michigan in fact throughout the country will come into this are nothing more than commercial enterprises for profit of its stockholders seeking residential mortgages primarily from the general public of all economic classes, rich, middle class, poor, just like any borrower from a bank, the testimony is uncontroverted from all the savings and loan officers and they were all hostile, that the borrower on the mortgage of the savings and loan association was no different than a borrower of bank that they passed upon that mortgage solely on his personal credit and on the security of his home.","start":1035.667,"stop":1093.859,"duration":58.19},{"text":"There was no difference.","start":1093.859,"stop":1095.895,"duration":2.04},{"text":"Now, what is the competition?","start":1095.895,"stop":1099.649,"duration":3.75},{"text":"We called as witnesses, 16 executive officers of each of the 16 savings and loan associations in the city, is where we did business.","start":1099.649,"stop":1112.261,"duration":12.61},{"text":"And each one of them admitted and I, again, say they were hostile that they -- their associations were the principal, dominant competitors of national banks, our bank, in other banks, in the business of residential mortgage loans.","start":1112.261,"stop":1135.423,"duration":23.16},{"text":"We obtained the recordings in the seven counties were we did business of all of the mortgages recorded in those counties for the year 1952, it's a very voluminous exhibit and there's abstract showing that the savings and loan associations were the largest principle mortgage lender in those counties.","start":1135.423,"stop":1164.178,"duration":28.76},{"text":"We subpoenaed the association reports showing the competition and we have the bank officers testified that in their opinion, the savings and loan associations or the principle and dominating competitor of Appellant Bank in the communities in which they awkward it.","start":1164.178,"stop":1186.748,"duration":22.57},{"text":"Their loans were on the same pro-types of property, they loaned of the same types of individual, they loaned to all classes of people, rich, middle class, poor, of all professions, business not just wage earners.","start":1186.748,"stop":1201.797,"duration":15.05},{"text":"That is undisputed.","start":1201.797,"stop":1203.878,"duration":2.08},{"text":"Now, if Your Honors would be good enough to look at page 17, because I think that tells the story --","start":1203.878,"stop":1209.962,"duration":6.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":1209.962,"stop":1210.735,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of our principle brief, our principle brief.","start":1210.735,"stop":1213.963,"duration":3.23},{"text":"We have a chart on page 17 of our principle brief.","start":1213.963,"stop":1226.15,"duration":12.19},{"text":"Page 17 sir.","start":1226.15,"stop":1229.445,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Now, the top line and this is all back by the testimony.","start":1229.445,"stop":1234.228,"duration":4.78},{"text":"The top line shows the seven cities in which the Appellant Bank operates.","start":1234.228,"stop":1240.067,"duration":5.84},{"text":"In 1952, our bank, in the seven cities had $60,000,000 of residential mortgage loans, some contract did in that year and in some priorities.","start":1240.067,"stop":1259.253,"duration":19.19},{"text":"The 16 savings and loan associations had $97,000,000 of loans in those same cities.","start":1259.253,"stop":1270.002,"duration":10.75},{"text":"Now, the next chart and these numbers might be helpful if you would write on the left side of the page 77 because that's the national banks in Michigan and on the right side of page 67, there were 77 national banks in Michigan, that's the left side of the page, and the right side of the page 67 associations, it shows that in 1952 the banks had $300,000,000 of residential mortgage loans, and the 67 101, savings and loan associations had $433,000,000, many contracted during the year 1952 on the same basis.","start":1270.002,"stop":1322.52,"duration":52.52},{"text":"Now, the next chart shows a comparison of national basis and then the very extraordinary and interesting thing is the 1957 figure which shows that in the five-year period from 1952 to 1957, savings and loan mortgage business increased three times greater than the mortgage loan business on residences of national banks.","start":1322.52,"stop":1358.307,"duration":35.79},{"text":"And we say with all humility and we've read the records in most of the leading cases on this subject, that we doubt that there's any case in which there has been such a showing of extensive and dominating competition by the other moneyed capital with the business of a national bank as we have demonstrated in this record.","start":1358.307,"stop":1390.082,"duration":31.78},{"text":"We say on the showing that we've made under the decisions of this Court, that the rate is greater the money invested by savings and loan associations and shares is other moneyed capital that this is substantial in amount, and it competes with the substantial phase of the business of national banks.","start":1390.082,"stop":1418.306,"duration":28.22},{"text":"You so decided in Hartford, Minnesota, Anderson, and Richmond.","start":1418.306,"stop":1426.063,"duration":7.76},{"text":"Now, we submit to the Court, that notwithstanding this showing of competition in a substantial vital phase of our business and I again point out that the residential mortgage loans in Appellant Bank were $60,000,000 and its commercial loans were only $22,000,000.","start":1426.063,"stop":1449.062,"duration":23},{"text":"In other words, their residential mortgage loan business was three times greater than our commercial loan business.","start":1449.062,"stop":1461.3,"duration":12.24},{"text":"We say notwithstanding that showing, the lower court in the appellee statute admitted extensive competition.","start":1461.3,"stop":1472.233,"duration":10.93},{"text":"In fact, you cannot have competition as a matter of law, because savings and loan associations are of a different character, purpose and organization.","start":1472.233,"stop":1494.259,"duration":22.03},{"text":"In other words, the appellee puts this question in its brief, how can fundamentally different institutions be in substantial competition under R.S. 5219?","start":1494.259,"stop":1507.726,"duration":13.47},{"text":"Pointing out that savings and loan associations under the Michigan law, under the federal law cannot accept deposits, cannot engage in the general banking business.","start":1507.726,"stop":1520.625,"duration":12.9},{"text":"Competition in fact is extensive, at minute, they dominate the fee.","start":1520.625,"stop":1528.39,"duration":7.77},{"text":"Carried to its final conclusion, this decision of the lower court in our opinion and the contention of appellee, means that there could be no business that could engage in the business of deposits or general banking except the bank.","start":1528.39,"stop":1547.921,"duration":19.53},{"text":"And following further, the only conclusion you can reach from that argument is that other moneyed capital means other banks.","start":1547.921,"stop":1559.518,"duration":11.6},{"text":"This Court in Hartford and in Richmond and in Minnesota has held directly to the contrary.","start":1559.518,"stop":1566.258,"duration":6.74},{"text":"Congress was act -- asked on two or three different occasions to limit the term \"other moneyed capital\" to other banks, and it refused to do so.","start":1566.258,"stop":1578.477,"duration":12.22},{"text":"The Michigan court and appellee contend contrary that the position taken by this Court and contrary to the act of Congress.","start":1578.477,"stop":1590.048,"duration":11.57},{"text":"The next point appellee makes -- says \"Well, savings and loan don't engage in all of the banking activities and therefore, you can't be in competition.\"","start":1590.048,"stop":1606.698,"duration":16.65},{"text":"And this Court also has decided in Hartford and in Minnesota that competition may exist under the statute even though the competition be with some but not all phases of the business of national banks.","start":1606.698,"stop":1626.249,"duration":19.55},{"text":"And on this character and nature proposition, this Court has said, competition in the sense intended arises not from the character of the business of those who compete, but from the manner of the employment of the capital at their command and pointed out the gross of various businesses not in the banking business, in phases of the business of national banks which if permitted to enjoy favored state taxation would place the national bank shares, those who invested in national bank shares any distinct and decided disadvantage.","start":1626.249,"stop":1679.53,"duration":53.28},{"text":"Then, the next argument appellee makes well even if one competitors in one phase and some competitors in another phase, you've got to show that this competes in all phases of the banking business have been favored by taxation.","start":1679.53,"stop":1699.092,"duration":19.56},{"text":"And this Court certainly has held to the contrary we believe, when it says a particular phase so long as that phase is substantial, substantial in amount and substantial when compared to the total capitalization of all banks.","start":1699.092,"stop":1718.551,"duration":19.46},{"text":"That this residential mortgage business is substantial in the case at bar, I again say is demonstrated when I tell you that 40% of Appellant's loans are in the residential mortgage business.","start":1718.551,"stop":1734.496,"duration":15.95},{"text":"We get 32% of our income, total income from the residential mortgage loans and it constitutes over 20% of our assets.","start":1734.496,"stop":1741.951,"duration":7.45},{"text":"And furthermore, this competition of savings and loan associations at that time $1.5 billion dollars in 1959 over $1.5 billion invested in shares was three times the total capitalization of all national banks in the State of Michigan which is the test this Court has laid down.","start":1741.951,"stop":1776.562,"duration":34.61},{"text":"Appellee says, or -- or the lower court says, this is too narrow field of the banking business, which as I pointed out.","start":1776.562,"stop":1784.735,"duration":8.17},{"text":"It's probably the most important field in the out state national banks today, and it's gotten to be a very important field in all nations.","start":1784.735,"stop":1795.195,"duration":10.46}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Klein --","start":1795.195,"stop":1795.813,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1795.813,"stop":1796.226,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I don't know whether it makes any difference, but I'm just wondering, is there any difference in the size of these loans --","start":1796.226,"stop":1803.425,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1803.425,"stop":1803.707,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that comes from the billing of loans in those companies.","start":1803.707,"stop":1806.918,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"They're all comparable size sir.","start":1806.918,"stop":1808.737,"duration":1.82},{"text":"The record is replete with.","start":1808.737,"stop":1810.48,"duration":1.74},{"text":"I don't -- we have exhibits, we asked witness after witness.","start":1810.48,"stop":1814.678,"duration":4.2},{"text":"They're the same type of loans and the same locality, the same type the houses.","start":1814.678,"stop":1819.578,"duration":4.9},{"text":"In fact, we have dozens and dozens of exhibits where, they, the associations refinanced the bank loans and the banks refinanced the association loans.","start":1819.578,"stop":1830.549,"duration":10.97},{"text":"We have pictures that we didn't put it in this exhibit showing the identical houses, the neighborhoods, the character, the type of people, they're the same, sir.","start":1830.549,"stop":1843.501,"duration":12.95},{"text":"They're all types of loans.","start":1843.501,"stop":1845.014,"duration":1.51},{"text":"There are some conventional loans, there are FHA loans, and there are VA loans.","start":1845.014,"stop":1850.726,"duration":5.71},{"text":"At that time, the associations took more conventional loans percentage-wise than we did, although we have many conventional loans.","start":1850.726,"stop":1860.556,"duration":9.83},{"text":"We took percentage-wise more FHA and VA loans then the savings and loan associations.","start":1860.556,"stop":1867.801,"duration":7.24},{"text":"Although -- yes, sir?","start":1867.801,"stop":1869.051,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I correctly understand that the question is not one of the facts of competition with one law --","start":1869.051,"stop":1875.971,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":1875.971,"stop":1876.142,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where there couldn't be competition.","start":1876.142,"stop":1877.819,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1877.819,"stop":1878.285,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that it?","start":1878.285,"stop":1878.987,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"That is it sir.","start":1878.987,"stop":1881.778,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What year was the last case involved in this question before this Court?","start":1881.778,"stop":1885.892,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"20 -- 912 involved in this competition question.","start":1885.892,"stop":1889.328,"duration":3.44},{"text":"In 1926, you had a subsequent case but this phase of the case was not discussed.","start":1889.328,"stop":1895.368,"duration":6.04},{"text":"There was the Hartford case and the Minnesota case --","start":1895.368,"stop":1898.653,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"1926?","start":1898.653,"stop":1899.524,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"1926.","start":1899.524,"stop":1901.125,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that under the national banks where they were the business?","start":1901.125,"stop":1904.89,"duration":3.77}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"They were to a small degree but they were sufficient for this Court to recognize that the competition of mortgage contenders individual partnerships and incorporations in the State of both Wisconsin and Minnesota was substantial enough to have the Court say that the discriminatory tax could not be maintained because of the competition sir, and that was the unanimous court in both to those cases.","start":1904.89,"stop":1938.377,"duration":33.49},{"text":"Now, the one point of shares the appellee claims, the lower court didn't get into this and I think Mr. Justice Harlan have said.","start":1938.377,"stop":1950.426,"duration":12.05},{"text":"The lower court didn't raise this question.","start":1950.426,"stop":1952.888,"duration":2.46},{"text":"But appellee now says, \"All these shares and savings and loan associations are not other moneyed capital, because they're like bank deposits, and commercial bank deposits aren't other moneyed capital.\"","start":1952.888,"stop":1978.118,"duration":25.23},{"text":"They raised this for the first time.","start":1978.118,"stop":1981.016,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Now, that position is directly contrary to the Michigan statute which provides that a payment for shares is for capital stock, capital stock.","start":1981.016,"stop":1996.858,"duration":15.84},{"text":"It's contrary to the bylaws of these associations which cause these payments, capital and provides for the issuance of shares and stock.","start":1996.858,"stop":2009.049,"duration":12.19},{"text":"It's contrary to the stock certificates which are -- coupled of which are attached to our reply brief wherein its whole capital stock and they're transferable in the manner of capital stock now in some instances, the certificates in a booklet.","start":2009.049,"stop":2028.52,"duration":19.47},{"text":"This -- this question was raised before the Michigan Supreme -- and -- and there's also a provision in the Michigan statute, that these associations cannot take deposits and that a shareholder of an association is not a creditor.","start":2028.52,"stop":2048.301,"duration":19.78},{"text":"So, how a shareholder could be a depositor if he couldn't be a creditor, and if the association couldn't take deposits as suggested by appellee is beyond us, but to go further, this counsel, the Attorney General of Michigan argued before the Michigan Supreme Court two years ago just as we are arguing before you today, and he took the position successfully in a case where the question was whether a state agency could invest in shares of savings and loan associations.","start":2048.301,"stop":2094.174,"duration":45.87},{"text":"The Savings & Loan League of Michigan attempted to have a determination that in substance, a share was lightly deposit and therefore, it didn't violate the constitutional injunction of Michigan against agencies purchasing shares in a corporation.","start":2094.174,"stop":2115.3,"duration":21.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, is that means of a -- they're speaking of some deposited state funds?","start":2115.3,"stop":2121.37,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":2121.37,"stop":2123.111,"duration":1.74},{"text":"And the Attorney General very enabling a sale the position of the Savings & Loan League, and pointed out and we put the quotation in our reply brief that payments on shares of savings and loan associations do not constitute deposits.","start":2123.111,"stop":2150.326,"duration":27.22},{"text":"And the Michigan Supreme Court said, in substance, in substance, they do not constitute deposit, but purchases of stock in a private corporation for profit.","start":2150.326,"stop":2165.935,"duration":15.61},{"text":"Those are the Attorney General's work on \"private corporation or profit.\"","start":2165.935,"stop":2171.892,"duration":5.96},{"text":"So we submit that this is moneyed capital, and it fits within the definition of this Court shares in a corporation or other interest of an individual put in an enterprise engaged in a business or profit.","start":2171.892,"stop":2196.335,"duration":24.44},{"text":"These are shares, they're stock, the statute says so, the case is so hold, the Attorney General of Michigan has always been of that opinion because there are a number of opinions which we've have cited.","start":2196.335,"stop":2208.638,"duration":12.3},{"text":"And the Michigan Supreme Court says that that is their relationship.","start":2208.638,"stop":2213.391,"duration":4.75},{"text":"And the language of the federal statute is also in terms of shares and capital.","start":2213.391,"stop":2221.653,"duration":8.26},{"text":"Now, we come to the next question, they say its other moneyed capital coming in competition was a substantial business of national banks and substantial in comparison with the capitalization of national banks.","start":2221.653,"stop":2246.159,"duration":24.51},{"text":"We say the question of greater rate requires no great debate.","start":2246.159,"stop":2251.194,"duration":5.03},{"text":"It can't be controverted that the rate is 13 times greater; it just takes simple mathematics $5.5 of thousand versus 40 cents of thousand.","start":2251.194,"stop":2264.235,"duration":13.04},{"text":"Now, on domestic corporation --associations in Michigan, there was a 25 cents of thousand in your privilege tax.","start":2264.235,"stop":2274.618,"duration":10.38},{"text":"So, even giving the domestic corporations credit for that, that would be $5.5 to 65 cents, eight times, 8:1, 13:1 in case of federal association.","start":2274.618,"stop":2293.293,"duration":18.68},{"text":"Now --","start":2293.293,"stop":2293.544,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) -- the other taxes?","start":2293.544,"stop":2295.072,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"The other taxes were unimportant sir.","start":2295.072,"stop":2297.699,"duration":2.63},{"text":"The both banks and associations have to pay the same type of real estate tax valued in the same manner at the same rate also unemployment taxes, both were subject.","start":2297.699,"stop":2309.891,"duration":12.19},{"text":"So, it becomes out -- there's an examination fee which we say it's for a service that banks have to pay an examination fee.","start":2309.891,"stop":2317.804,"duration":7.91},{"text":"There were few other taxes which we've listed in our brief, but it's very inconsequential sir, and I think for all practical purposes, we can say 13:1 in cases of federal associations, 13 -- 8:1 domestic corporations.","start":2317.804,"stop":2335.354,"duration":17.55},{"text":"So what does the appellee do in the court below?","start":2335.354,"stop":2339.227,"duration":3.87},{"text":"He urged the proposition directly contrary to the position of this Court and the Michigan Court followed.","start":2339.227,"stop":2346.611,"duration":7.38},{"text":"He said, \"Because, we're dealing with two different types of organizations here, one that takes deposit does lot of business with deposits and one that does not.\"","start":2346.611,"stop":2360.913,"duration":14.3},{"text":"This tax shouldn't be on shares, it ought to be measured by the tax burden on total assets of each institution.","start":2360.913,"stop":2372.167,"duration":11.25},{"text":"In other words, if we figured out how many dollars of taxes banks paid or the bank in our bank pay and took the ratio of total assets without deducting the deposit liability of it and did the same thing for savings and loan which didn't borrow very much because they are a more conservative operation in banks in that respect that we have that liability.","start":2372.167,"stop":2399.787,"duration":27.62},{"text":"Why?","start":2399.787,"stop":2400.357,"duration":0.57},{"text":"They said there is substantial equality.","start":2400.357,"stop":2404.462,"duration":4.11},{"text":"Now, to do that required and rewriting in the statute, this is a tax on shares not on gross assets of the corporation.","start":2404.462,"stop":2415.387,"duration":10.93},{"text":"And this Court held, when this very same proposition was urged to this Court in Minnesota in 1926.","start":2415.387,"stop":2426.891,"duration":11.5},{"text":"The argument ignores the fact that the tax authorized by 5219 is against the holders of the bank shares, and is measured by the value of the shares and not by the assets of the bank without deduction of its liabilities.","start":2426.891,"stop":2450.729,"duration":23.84},{"text":"In other words, it's a tax on the shares not on the assets of a corporation without deducting its liabilities to ascertain the equity of the shares.","start":2450.729,"stop":2466.3,"duration":15.57},{"text":"The Minnesota -- this Court Minnesota completely rejected without qualification that argument.","start":2466.3,"stop":2476.256,"duration":9.96},{"text":"Now, the appellee -- and the Michigan Court followed the rule which is directly contrary to this Court in Minnesota.","start":2476.256,"stop":2484.794,"duration":8.54},{"text":"Now, the appellee urges that this Court considered a different tax, just ignored the fact that the share of capital, and only take the reserves and undivided profits of the savings and loan associations.","start":2484.794,"stop":2501.948,"duration":17.15},{"text":"And if you did that, you might get approximate equality.","start":2501.948,"stop":2506.01,"duration":4.06},{"text":"First place, the Michigan statute doesn't permit that.","start":2506.01,"stop":2509.083,"duration":3.07},{"text":"The Michigan statute says, \"This is a tax on the shares of savings and loan and only the paid up capitals for that part.\"","start":2509.083,"stop":2517.286,"duration":8.2},{"text":"It talks not about the undivided profits, and if the tax under paid up capital of the national bank and its undivided profits and its service.","start":2517.286,"stop":2529.509,"duration":12.22},{"text":"We submit that under the rulings of this Court going back to Weaver and Hepburn which cited in our brief, that where you have the same type of taxation which you do here, this is not a question of different methods of taxation.","start":2529.509,"stop":2547.742,"duration":18.23},{"text":"Any tax which exacts from the owner of the shares, a larger sum in proportion to their actual value than it does from the owner of other moneyed capital, valued in a light manner thus tax them at a greater rate.","start":2547.742,"stop":2566.638,"duration":18.9},{"text":"It doesn't just decide in one case, the shares are invested in a corporation which borrows little money and some shares are invested in the corporation which borrows more money and a bank has a lot of indebtedness to bank deposit.","start":2566.638,"stop":2584.693,"duration":18.06},{"text":"It doesn't say that that Congress has said, once we determine that this is other moneyed capital and it comes in competition substantially, rate valued in the same manner, if it's the same type of tax is the determining bank.","start":2584.693,"stop":2606.897,"duration":22.2},{"text":"Now, the last point, and that's the point upon which I think appellee and the lower court relied very heavily a so-called \"partial exemption ordinance.\"","start":2606.897,"stop":2621.695,"duration":14.8},{"text":"There were some old cases, going back to the 1800s up till 1899 are originally when moneyed capital was not as its now defined when it wasn't -- its inventory wasn't money.","start":2621.695,"stop":2641.692,"duration":20},{"text":"It's all intenders of any kind didn't have to come in competition with the bank in the old days.","start":2641.692,"stop":2652.29,"duration":10.6},{"text":"And some portion, not material, was exempt noncompeting.","start":2652.29,"stop":2661.059,"duration":8.77},{"text":"The Court in those days said, \"There could be a partial exemption.","start":2661.059,"stop":2667.341,"duration":6.28},{"text":"It was not in competition and it was not moneyed capital as now defined.\"","start":2667.341,"stop":2675.202,"duration":7.86},{"text":"If it was a material, even though not in competition, there was violation.","start":2675.202,"stop":2681.001,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Then when the Court decided Mercantile and throughout the years and limited moneyed capital to only those businesses share -- which -- which shares were had, which business was moneyed.","start":2681.001,"stop":2697.04,"duration":16.04},{"text":"The competition became the dominant factor, and not for 61 years has this Court ever mentioned partial exemption anymore in any case.","start":2697.04,"stop":2709.127,"duration":12.09},{"text":"But even if there is a partial exemption doctrine now, we say there is not.","start":2709.127,"stop":2714.706,"duration":5.58},{"text":"We say that's been gone with this new principle of coming into competition was a substantial phase of the business through the bank.","start":2714.706,"stop":2723.562,"duration":8.86},{"text":"But even if that doctrine applies, the appellee presents to this Court the most extraordinary proposition.","start":2723.562,"stop":2733.475,"duration":9.91},{"text":"He contends that the State of Michigan having granted partial exemption to shares of savings and loan associations, this Court is foreclosed from considering whether or not there was just cause from the -- for the State exempting from taxes something which might violate that federal statute which have just caused to exempt something under a federal statute and he suggests this Court can't even consider that question.","start":2733.475,"stop":2774.799,"duration":41.32},{"text":"We submit in the first place, that although originally savings and loan associations were exempt by Michigan statute, they no longer are.","start":2774.799,"stop":2786.535,"duration":11.74},{"text":"They are subject to taxes, and there is no partial exemption that tax is on all of the shares but add 1/13th of the rate.","start":2786.535,"stop":2798.25,"duration":11.72},{"text":"That isn't a partial exemption, that's a preference a tax of discrimination.","start":2798.25,"stop":2803.836,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the privilege allowed (Inaudible) tax?","start":2803.836,"stop":2807.632,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2807.632,"stop":2808.654,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Just as a bank saving.","start":2808.654,"stop":2809.702,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2809.702,"stop":2811.71,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Now, in arriving at this so-called just cost, appellee relies on old cases at a time one, when national banks could not be in the mortgage business.","start":2811.71,"stop":2829.612,"duration":17.9},{"text":"It's only been permitted to have mortgages since 1916 and really in real volume since 1933, a work permitted to take savings until 1927 by statute.","start":2829.612,"stop":2840.072,"duration":10.46},{"text":"They weren't in the competition factually or otherwise with savings and loan associations in those days.","start":2840.072,"stop":2856.269,"duration":16.2},{"text":"Now, on the just cause for exemption --","start":2856.269,"stop":2858.861,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the reason for the exemption?","start":2858.861,"stop":2861.316,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"In the old days, sir?","start":2861.316,"stop":2862.404,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2862.404,"stop":2863.905,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"First, the savings bank cases.","start":2863.905,"stop":2866.281,"duration":2.38},{"text":"They dealt with poor people of limited means who had no place to put their savings and no place to get mortgages.","start":2866.281,"stop":2875.94,"duration":9.66},{"text":"And they -- in the savings bank cases, they were publicly managed.","start":2875.94,"stop":2881.913,"duration":5.97},{"text":"The -- the trustees were appointed by the State not by the depositors.","start":2881.913,"stop":2887.292,"duration":5.38},{"text":"Now, the savings and loan associations in the older days and Justice Taft -- then Judge Taft commented in an early case in 1890 or something that they were comprised of poor people who banded together under a mutual thrift plan to afford a facility from which they could borrow money.","start":2887.292,"stop":2915.926,"duration":28.63},{"text":"And that, and that I -- that worked in this way and Michigan had the same case.","start":2915.926,"stop":2920.997,"duration":5.07},{"text":"It was quasi charitable, nonprofit, noncommercial, because you had to be a borrower, you had to be a stockholder, and he could only bid for a loan to the extent that he has subscribed for his stock.","start":2920.997,"stop":2939.471,"duration":18.47},{"text":"He couldn't bid more.","start":2939.471,"stop":2940.631,"duration":1.16},{"text":"In other words, in the old days if I were a poor man which I might qualify filed -- I had to be a stockholder, I've signed up for $1000 worth of stock and agreed to pay $2 or $5 a week.","start":2940.631,"stop":2957.226,"duration":16.6},{"text":"And then, when the money was bid on, I could come and bid for it in competition with other stockholders, but I can only bid up to the amount of my stock subscription.","start":2957.226,"stop":2968.468,"duration":11.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Did have.","start":2968.468,"stop":2969.274,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or a mortgage against the other members who own stock.","start":2969.274,"stop":2973.209,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"For a loan?","start":2973.209,"stop":2974.057,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"For a loan.","start":2974.057,"stop":2975.123,"duration":1.07},{"text":"He had to pay a premium in those days.","start":2975.123,"stop":2979.305,"duration":4.18},{"text":"Then he would get a loan for $1000 and he'd have to pay on his stock subscription.","start":2979.305,"stop":2987.927,"duration":8.62},{"text":"The only thing he paid on his mortgage was interest.","start":2987.927,"stop":2991.932,"duration":4},{"text":"He paid so much a week on his stock subscription and if the -- there was money profit made, the dividends would pay -- be paid to him and he could then use that to pay his interest.","start":2991.932,"stop":3007.048,"duration":15.12},{"text":"If there were losses, he got no dividends or received no dividends.","start":3007.048,"stop":3010.93,"duration":3.88},{"text":"And in case of a failure, and this is the importance, he had to pay his mortgage loan 100% in full, received no credit for what he had paid on the stock.","start":3010.93,"stop":3028.541,"duration":17.61},{"text":"In fact, he might have had to pay the balance of his subscription of general creditors when it's answered.","start":3028.541,"stop":3034.22,"duration":5.68},{"text":"So, he was on both sides of the deal.","start":3034.22,"stop":3039.522,"duration":5.3},{"text":"It was a cooperative, noncommercial neutral enterprise.","start":3039.522,"stop":3044.426,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On that basis, the State decided a good (Voice Overlap) --","start":3044.426,"stop":3046.799,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Exempt, but it doesn't exempt in anymore sir.","start":3046.799,"stop":3050.018,"duration":3.22},{"text":"The Federal Government removed the exemption in 1951 and we quoted the part in there and they're to be taxed, it was the intent of Congress that these associations be taxed just like other corporations.","start":3050.018,"stop":3066.059,"duration":16.04},{"text":"Now, in 1935, the State of Michigan amended the Home Owners Act and we've got a little writer on page 72 of our principle brief.","start":3066.059,"stop":3077.522,"duration":11.46},{"text":"I hope it's been appended to all of your briefs.","start":3077.522,"stop":3080.241,"duration":2.72},{"text":"It's page 76, Your Honor.","start":3080.241,"stop":3083.537,"duration":3.3},{"text":"Pointing out that in 1935, the stat -- this Section was amended so no longer does a stockholder -- does a borrower have to own stock in order to take a loan.","start":3083.537,"stop":3098.663,"duration":15.13},{"text":"In other words, he doesn't have to be an investor and he doesn't -- he can borrow any amount regardless of what his stock ownership may be.","start":3098.663,"stop":3108.512,"duration":9.85},{"text":"He doesn't even have to be a stock ownership before he can only borrow to the extent of his stock ownership.","start":3108.512,"stop":3114.22,"duration":5.71}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So you've appended a right (Voice Overlap) --","start":3114.22,"stop":3115.729,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we've asked that it'd be appended on page 76.","start":3115.729,"stop":3119.061,"duration":3.33},{"text":"We asked the clerk to do it.","start":3119.061,"stop":3120.454,"duration":1.39},{"text":"Now, he may have failed to do so.","start":3120.454,"stop":3122.488,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it is (Inaudible)","start":3122.488,"stop":3124.1,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we will -- we will ask the clerk to do it again.","start":3124.1,"stop":3128.38,"duration":4.28},{"text":"We have extra copy because that calls your attention to this one.","start":3128.38,"stop":3131.114,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It carried it out but not by fixing it under the case.","start":3131.114,"stop":3134.174,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"I see, sir.","start":3134.174,"stop":3136.75,"duration":2.58},{"text":"Now, that is a significant change because now, there is no mutuality and stockholders are from all economic classes, corporations, trust, pension trust, professional men, businessmen, they're out solely for the profit and borrowers are out solely to get the best loans they have.","start":3136.75,"stop":3165.061,"duration":28.31},{"text":"There's no mutuality of interest.","start":3165.061,"stop":3167.345,"duration":2.28},{"text":"One is just like a -- any stock in a -- in a corporation where you're out to get as much profit as you can and the borrower is out to get as much as he -- to the best loan he can get.","start":3167.345,"stop":3180.762,"duration":13.42},{"text":"And the class of investors are all classes across the board, no longer poor people.","start":3180.762,"stop":3189.869,"duration":9.11},{"text":"As I say, there is advertising campaigns locally, statewide, nationally.","start":3189.869,"stop":3196.524,"duration":6.65},{"text":"In fact, over the weekend, there were two national, big national corporations, football games, savings and loan people seeking to get investors of all classes, corporations otherwise to invest in their stock or savings and loan associations seeking to get borrowers of all classes.","start":3196.524,"stop":3216.608,"duration":20.08},{"text":"And it's no different in a bank they compete for the mortgage business just as they do in the case of banks and there is no just reasons, no just reasons why they should enjoy a preference, and it is a preference, it's not an exemption in state taxation in view of the injunction of Congress that a State shall not pass this other moneyed capital at a greater rate than national banks.","start":3216.608,"stop":3248.5,"duration":31.89},{"text":"And if there's every been a time when our fiscal policy and our economic stability had to be safeguard, I think most responsible people are in agreement that such time is now and in encroachment of this kind against national banks would be very serious indeed.","start":3248.5,"stop":3272.769,"duration":24.27}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3272.769,"stop":3276.289,"duration":3.52}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 19, 1961","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren7/oral_argument_audio/14103","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Michigan National Bank et al., Appellants, versus Michigan et al.","start":0,"stop":6.512,"duration":6.51},{"text":"Mr. Klein, had you concluded your argument?","start":6.512,"stop":8.814,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"I should like to reserve the remaining time for rebuttal.","start":8.814,"stop":11.911,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may -- you may.","start":11.911,"stop":14.374,"duration":2.46},{"text":"Mr. Dexter.","start":14.374,"stop":21.229,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the members of the Court.","start":21.229,"stop":27.235,"duration":6.01},{"text":"The essential question here involves the validity of a Michigan statute imposed upon the shares of the appellant bank.","start":27.235,"stop":44.23,"duration":16.99},{"text":"It's a 5 1/2-mill tax.","start":44.23,"stop":47.735,"duration":3.51},{"text":"It is measured by the capital account of the appellant bank that represents 4% of the appellant bank's employable assets.","start":47.735,"stop":57.523,"duration":9.79},{"text":"The trial court in response to the same kind of argument that the appellant has presented here both by brief and by oral argument, decided that the restrictions imposed on the State of Michigan to tax national bank shares had not been violated.","start":57.523,"stop":78.846,"duration":21.32},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Michigan, by a unanimous decision arrived at the same conclusion.","start":78.846,"stop":87.091,"duration":8.24},{"text":"Now, frankly, everything that the appellant has brought before this Court in argument has been answered thrice by the appellees both in the trial court, in the Supreme Court of Michigan and I believe quite comprehensively and adequately by the appellees' brief filed in this Court.","start":87.091,"stop":109.946,"duration":22.86},{"text":"I do believe, however, that it would be helpful to this Court to see the issue in this case put in a proper setting.","start":109.946,"stop":125.581,"duration":15.64},{"text":"I would then begin by informing the Court generally, of the tax picture in Michigan concerning the taxation of financial businesses.","start":125.581,"stop":137.845,"duration":12.26},{"text":"Now, prior to 1952, the State of Michigan did not impose any tax on national bank stock.","start":137.845,"stop":149.308,"duration":11.46},{"text":"It did impose a 4-mill franchise privilege fee on banks and trust companies under the General Corporation Law.","start":149.308,"stop":160.196,"duration":10.89},{"text":"This tax is measured by paid-up capital and surplus of each of these institutions.","start":160.196,"stop":168.306,"duration":8.11},{"text":"This tax, the 4-mill tax on paid-up capital and surplus, the annual franchise privilege fee in Michigan imposed on all corporations, was also paid generally by financial corporations in the State of Michigan.","start":168.306,"stop":187.984,"duration":19.68},{"text":"Also in 1952 and prior thereto, the general financial businesses in terms of their intangible properties were subject to a tax of 3.5% on the dividends paid or received by such corporations on their stock holdings.","start":187.984,"stop":212.747,"duration":24.76},{"text":"Also, there was a tax of 1/25 of 1% on various intangible properties classified as accounts receivable.","start":212.747,"stop":224.518,"duration":11.77},{"text":"In addition, under the General Intangibles Tax Act, there was imposed the tax of 40 cents per 1000 that the appellant refers to, on cash deposits in all banking and financial institutions and savings and loan share account moneys.","start":224.518,"stop":247.42,"duration":22.9},{"text":"In addition, in 1952 and prior thereto, the State of Michigan imposed on domestic savings and loan associations, a franchise fee measured by 1/4 mill of the pay -- of the savings share account and legal reserve moneys of each state institution.","start":247.42,"stop":274.138,"duration":26.72},{"text":"Now, by a series of amendments in 1954, federal savings and loan associations were subjected to the same tax.","start":274.138,"stop":284.627,"duration":10.49},{"text":"In addition, the financial businesses generally, were subject to some miscellaneous taxes to which appellant bank was not subject.","start":284.627,"stop":295.499,"duration":10.87}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"In federal -- in federal and state loan associations are the tax comparative?","start":295.499,"stop":302.033,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, up until -- in 1952, the State of Michigan had not imposed this 1/4 mill franchise tax, but in 1954, they did, yes.","start":302.033,"stop":312.986,"duration":10.95},{"text":"Currently now, they're on a parity. --","start":312.986,"stop":314.606,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"A parity?","start":314.606,"stop":316.611,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn’t fit -- yes.","start":316.611,"stop":317.52,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn’t find -- have you finished answering?","start":317.52,"stop":320.021,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":324.601,"stop":320.021,"duration":-4.58},{"text":"I -- I think that I have if I've answered Your Honor's question.","start":320.021,"stop":324.8,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I want to know is whether this recital of Michigan legislation affecting various groups of financial institutions and more particularly, the taxations in which under various enactments, not now under review here, is that right?","start":324.8,"stop":342.757,"duration":17.96}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":342.757,"stop":343.441,"duration":0.68},{"text":"These -- these are the -- these are the --","start":343.441,"stop":346.27,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but --","start":346.27,"stop":346.482,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the statute under consideration here, except in 1952, the State of Michigan removed state banks and trust companies from the 4-mill tax on the corporate privilege fee and removed the dividends and income from their stock from the 3 1/2-mill intangibles to or that the tax measured by 3.5% of income from -- income-producing intangibles, which would include the stock of the appellant bank and in lieu of these two taxes by Act 9 of the Public Acts of 1953, imposed the 5 1/2-mill tax we have before the Court, now.","start":346.482,"stop":397.183,"duration":50.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I -- I -- what I meant to ask requires a more detailed statement.","start":397.183,"stop":402.809,"duration":5.63},{"text":"What we have under attack -- under attack is a particular tax claimed to be discriminatory because competing state institutions are not subject to it, is that right?","start":402.809,"stop":413.099,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right, Your Honor.","start":413.099,"stop":413.993,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in order -- in dealing with the question of discrimination, there or not, did I correctly understand you to lay before the Court a system, a network of taxation to which these so called favored state institutions are subject?","start":413.993,"stop":435.933,"duration":21.94}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":435.933,"stop":436.784,"duration":0.85},{"text":"I meant to say that -- I was giving the Court the picture of the general treatment in Michigan --","start":436.784,"stop":442.696,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I under --","start":442.696,"stop":443.064,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of financial institutions --","start":443.064,"stop":444.176,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well --","start":444.176,"stop":444.884,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in 1952.","start":444.884,"stop":446.13,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And so is -- and that's what my question is directed to.","start":446.13,"stop":449.069,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":449.069,"stop":449.118,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether your purpose in doing so is to show starting with the assumption that in dealing -- in passing on the constitutional validity or the conflict between subjection of a federal instrumentality from which a state instrumentality is free in order to determine whether there is such a discrimination, one must take into account the whole network of taxation of the State in order to find out whether, although the federal institutions maybe subject to a tax from which a state institution is free, conversely, the state institutions maybe subject to obligations from which the federal institution is free.","start":449.118,"stop":494.342,"duration":45.22}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right.","start":494.342,"stop":495.371,"duration":1.03},{"text":"This Court has said in a number of decisions interpreting Section 5219, that the practical operative effect of the total tax burden on alleged competing financial institutions is the test to be employed.","start":495.371,"stop":514.53,"duration":19.16},{"text":"And I am showing not only the total financial burden tax wise by the State of Michigan, on the alleged competing institutions here, but also on the general financial businesses, because I think this is significant in relationship to this Court's repeated pronouncement that only tax discriminations intended to create or foster a hostile or unfriendly attitude for the business of national banks is prohibited.","start":514.53,"stop":548.569,"duration":34.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But even if in fact or -- or if in fact the discrimination is worse, it's in fact, a statute is passed levying a tax upon state financial institution in competition with national banks and not levied on national institutions, this Court doesn't have to find out whether you had a sinister purpose or whether you -- whether you thought this would or would not advantage state institutions if in fact, in construing, in applying with practical financial result of legislature, we don’t have to go and to search whether the purpose was a hostile one, as against the federal banks.","start":548.569,"stop":592.774,"duration":44.21}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":592.774,"stop":593.488,"duration":0.71},{"text":"It's certainly is not a subjective --","start":593.488,"stop":595.196,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":595.196,"stop":595.76,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- test.","start":595.76,"stop":596.179,"duration":0.42},{"text":"It's an objective test and this is the kind of test that we have employed in developing our case here, that is looking to the actual realities of the taxation of the two alleged competing institutions and see exactly how in terms of competition and in terms of real discrimination in terms of this competition.","start":596.179,"stop":624.164,"duration":27.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- including the total tax incidence of the State.","start":624.164,"stop":628.434,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right or yes --","start":628.434,"stop":629.88,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":629.88,"stop":630.59,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":630.59,"stop":631.025,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":631.025,"stop":649.738,"duration":18.71}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"The savings and loan associations.","start":649.738,"stop":651.15,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":651.15,"stop":656.09,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me start --","start":656.09,"stop":657.518,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was reversed and the compliments --","start":657.518,"stop":659.527,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":659.527,"stop":660.14,"duration":0.61},{"text":"Alright the only --","start":660.14,"stop":660.438,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- compliments, so far --","start":660.438,"stop":661.171,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":661.171,"stop":661.54,"duration":0.37},{"text":"The only tax imposed on national banks in 1952 by the State of Michigan was the 5 1/2-mill tax imposed by an amendment of the general Intangibles Tax Law by Act 9 of the Michigan Public Acts of 1953.","start":661.54,"stop":680.161,"duration":18.62},{"text":"This tax plus the tax on the real property of the bank constituted the sole tax burden to the State of Michigan, which incidentally represented about 8/10 -- 9/10th of a mill on the total employable assets of the appellant bank, but this was their total tax burden.","start":680.161,"stop":702.162,"duration":22},{"text":"Now, as distinguished from that burden, the savings and loan associations pay a tax of 40 cents per 1000 on the share accounts.","start":702.162,"stop":716.292,"duration":14.13},{"text":"And also, depositors in banks paid a tax of 40 cents per 1000, but this tax was absorbed by the banks and generally is in Michigan.","start":716.292,"stop":730.018,"duration":13.73},{"text":"But in addition to the 40 cents per $1000 tax on Michigan savings and loan shares including the federal, the state savings and loans only in 1952 and both state and federal in 1954, paid a 1/4 of a mill franchise tax to the Secretary of State's office, measured by the total share account and the legal reserves of each institution.","start":730.018,"stop":757.873,"duration":27.86},{"text":"Also, the savings and loan associations in Michigan were subject to a lot of miscellaneous taxes that the national banks could not be subjected to because of the restrictions imposed on a state's power by Section 5219.","start":757.873,"stop":775.373,"duration":17.5},{"text":"This includes a personal property tax.","start":775.373,"stop":778.346,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It would --","start":778.346,"stop":778.644,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you've given -- you've given -- you've indicated different units of measure or different -- or different basis of the taxation as between the two classes of institution, is it not?","start":778.644,"stop":790.152,"duration":11.51}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is true, Your Honor.","start":790.152,"stop":791.15,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, could you translate that or equate that into more or less equivalent terms and see where you come up?","start":791.15,"stop":798.214,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I would -- I would like to do that and I think that this can be accomplished by an examination of the competitive facts and circumstances of this case.","start":798.214,"stop":812.034,"duration":13.82},{"text":"Now, appellant bank's capital account, that is the subject of this 5 1/2-mill tax we're here concerned with, represented 4% of its employable assets.","start":812.034,"stop":824.891,"duration":12.86},{"text":"In other words, it was $13,000,000 out of $306,000,000.","start":824.891,"stop":830.269,"duration":5.38},{"text":"The balance of the appellant's employable assets made -- was made up of deposit money of $283,000,000 and these moneys, $283,000,000, $157,000,000 were demand deposits, the balance were time deposits of one kind or another.","start":830.269,"stop":854.113,"duration":23.84},{"text":"Now, also in 1952, this equity capital, this capital that the appellant is talking about in reference to Section 5219 was able to command in the loan activity, a loan, approximately 12 times the assets of a dollar value of a savings and loan share account.","start":854.113,"stop":879.077,"duration":24.96},{"text":"It was able to command in the financial field, $23 to $1 of the capital account.","start":879.077,"stop":887.29,"duration":8.21},{"text":"It was able to produce in 1952 a net profit of 31.5% before federal income taxes on the total capital account of the appellant bank which translated into the original investment in the appellant bank by stock holders in 1941, amounted to several hundred percent return on the original capital investment.","start":887.29,"stop":913.168,"duration":25.88},{"text":"This can be translated also into an analogy with the facts, all the savings and loan people.","start":913.168,"stop":924.959,"duration":11.79},{"text":"The savings and loan people allegedly in competition with the business of national -- the appellant national bank in Michigan in 1952, had total share account moneys of $143,000,000, mutual moneys pooled by savers, which was less than the appellant's demand deposits on which it paid no interest.","start":924.959,"stop":950.894,"duration":25.94},{"text":"These share account moneys were able to use or able to produce only 3.3% return.","start":950.894,"stop":960.604,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Now, we simply are essentially saying that the appellant bank with the broad powers given a national bank in association, with the ability to create checkbook money, with the exclusive ability to receive deposit moneys, is in a position economically to really employ equity capital and that a -- in a dollar investment in a share of national bank stock, is an entirely different thing than a so called investment in a savings and loan share account dollar.","start":960.604,"stop":1003.719,"duration":43.12},{"text":"For this reason, the only expert testimony produced in this cause, Professor Woodward, of the University of Michigan, a professor of finance and taxation said that, \"If you wanted to make a competitive that economic comparison of these two institutions in a realistic manner, you had to look to what each institution had to compete with, namely so many dollars.\"","start":1003.719,"stop":1036.795,"duration":33.08},{"text":"Essentially, we say then that the appellant bank equipped with these broad powers, could employ a -- on a ratio of 23 to 1 assets, in the residential mortgage market or any other activity it sought to engage in.","start":1036.795,"stop":1056.837,"duration":20.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you saying they're not in competition or are you saying that the national bank, the appellants here had more power for resources at their disposal in competing with?","start":1056.837,"stop":1069.618,"duration":12.78}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I think that that question really interrelated and let me say why.","start":1069.618,"stop":1078.154,"duration":8.54},{"text":"Tax discrimination or rate discrimination as the appellant would phrase it, under Section 5219, is only the kind of discrimination by a state that can be said to discourage an investment in a national bank stock and to that end places the business of national banks at a competitive disadvantage.","start":1078.154,"stop":1106.08,"duration":27.93},{"text":"And we simply say as long as savings and loan share accounts, impossibly employed in competition in the residential mortgage market admittedly with the deposit money of the appellant bank are treated equally, there really isn't any discrimination in fact and none can be read into Section 5219.","start":1106.08,"stop":1129.385,"duration":23.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the question is, \"Are they treated equally in that effect?\"","start":1129.385,"stop":1131.845,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1131.845,"stop":1132.428,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The question is, \"Are they treated equally?\"","start":1132.428,"stop":1134.351,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"The competitive units, Your Honor, are treated equal.","start":1134.351,"stop":1138.428,"duration":4.08}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is by the State -- by the State?","start":1138.428,"stop":1139.705,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1139.705,"stop":1140.489,"duration":0.78},{"text":"The bank actually, in 1952, employed its deposit money and primarily its time deposit money under the Comptroller's regulations, in a residential mortgage market.","start":1140.489,"stop":1155.658,"duration":15.17},{"text":"And there primarily in a field guaranteed by the Federal Government so these assets could be considered liquid by the bank.","start":1155.658,"stop":1164.055,"duration":8.4},{"text":"On the other hand, the savings and loan share account money was employed in the same way.","start":1164.055,"stop":1170.777,"duration":6.72},{"text":"Now, these have been taxed equally by the State of Michigan.","start":1170.777,"stop":1173.984,"duration":3.21},{"text":"Then if you step back and take the total asset -- the total asset comparison that we have used in our brief, you'll come up with equal taxation.","start":1173.984,"stop":1182.305,"duration":8.32},{"text":"If you took a gross income to gross income comparison, you come up with equivalent taxation.","start":1182.305,"stop":1188.863,"duration":6.56},{"text":"If you take the capitalization of earnings at the same rate of return, you come up with equal taxation.","start":1188.863,"stop":1197.651,"duration":8.79},{"text":"And we say, under these kinds of circumstances, there really isn't anything for the appellant to complain about within the purview of Section 5219.","start":1197.651,"stop":1208.781,"duration":11.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you also -- I beg your pardon.","start":1208.781,"stop":1212.013,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I was -- I was just trying to follow up Justice Frankfurter's question because I don't quite understand yet the difference.","start":1212.013,"stop":1221.631,"duration":9.62},{"text":"I wonder if put this way, as I understood your adversary, he says that his bank has to pay 13 times more taxes than the building and loans, but you say that's not true.","start":1221.631,"stop":1237.108,"duration":15.48},{"text":"What is the basis that would bring about such a tremendous difference (Inaudible)","start":1237.108,"stop":1243.358,"duration":6.25}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I --","start":1243.358,"stop":1244.601,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just relating to the same thing.","start":1244.601,"stop":1245.902,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I know what it is and I think I can explain it.","start":1245.902,"stop":1249.508,"duration":3.61},{"text":"The appellant says, \"Our capital is this $13,000,000 in terms of talking about rate discrimination and he compares to 5 1/2 mills on the $13,000,000 or the capital account or equity capital of the appellant bank and forgets, for purposes of the talking about discrimination, all of the deposit money that it called, borrowed capital.","start":1249.508,"stop":1279.056,"duration":29.55}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You say then that he doesn't consider his capital to be a not, is that it?","start":1279.056,"stop":1283.087,"duration":4.03}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"We say that -- Your Honor that if you take -- really, we have a two-pronged practical argument at this level.","start":1283.087,"stop":1290.944,"duration":7.86},{"text":"And is simply this, that if the capital of the appellant as defined in Section 5219, is limited to equity capital, we could say, \"Yes, there is a discrimination rate wise here.\"","start":1290.944,"stop":1306.046,"duration":15.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"13 -- 13 times?","start":1306.046,"stop":1307.785,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would not be that because he had -- they have not taken in the total tax picture.","start":1307.785,"stop":1313.692,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1313.692,"stop":1315.036,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they -- they got the 8 from the -- in reference to the state associations that paid that 1/4 of a mill and he got the 13 from leaving this 1/4 of a mill out.","start":1315.036,"stop":1323.934,"duration":8.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would make a difference if true, whether it's 8 or 13, would it?","start":1323.934,"stop":1327.084,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it wouldn't make any difference so we aren't -- we don't -- it maybe 6 if you actually worked it out but again, this wouldn't make any difference.","start":1327.084,"stop":1335.545,"duration":8.46},{"text":"Exhibit 213 shows that -- that the tax is on these institutions and compared them across the board.","start":1335.545,"stop":1342.176,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're doing -- and will you be good enough unless you have -- have not, have you finished --","start":1342.176,"stop":1346.646,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not.","start":1346.646,"stop":1346.814,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in answering Justice Black?","start":1346.814,"stop":1347.667,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- yes, I haven't finished this yet, you see.","start":1347.667,"stop":1349.457,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what I want to know.","start":1349.457,"stop":1349.972,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1349.972,"stop":1350.304,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that here -- at this level, you could say, \"Why, yes, there are -- there is tax discrimination.\"","start":1350.304,"stop":1355.718,"duration":5.41},{"text":"And of course, at -- at this level also, you have to say that a savings share account is like an equity investment in a share of national bank stock and I think this Court is well aware of the difference between a share of stock and a deposit in a savings and loan share account that the latter is analogous to a bank deposit.","start":1355.718,"stop":1381.131,"duration":25.41},{"text":"But then, the appellant without tying in its discrimination argument, jumps over and talks about substantial competition.","start":1381.131,"stop":1392.142,"duration":11.01},{"text":"But when it talks about competition under 5219, it's talking about the employment of the deposit moneys of the bank, you see and we simply say under this kind of situation, we don't care whether you talk about the deposits being part of the capital of the bank or not.","start":1392.142,"stop":1415.083,"duration":22.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Just as you're saying that you --","start":1415.083,"stop":1416.191,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1416.191,"stop":1416.43,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say that?","start":1416.43,"stop":1417.733,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Which do I say?","start":1417.733,"stop":1418.811,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1418.811,"stop":1419.202,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think, Your Honor on --","start":1419.202,"stop":1420.029,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The deposits, do you call them capital or not (Inaudible)","start":1420.029,"stop":1423.123,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the decisions of this Court in the Clement National Bank case, I think they ruled out deposits from being the capital of the bank, but I think also, they ruled out in that case, specifically any protection over the taxation or employment of this kind of money.","start":1423.123,"stop":1446.974,"duration":23.85},{"text":"So that we say that -- that the capital of the bank has not been established by this in this case factually, to have been in any competition with the savings and loan businesses, but rather that they have used a portion of their time deposits.","start":1446.974,"stop":1464.188,"duration":17.21},{"text":"But we've backed off from this and said, \"Even though this is true, let's look at the total picture of the two institutions.\"","start":1464.188,"stop":1471.739,"duration":7.55},{"text":"The practical operative effect of the Michigan's tax structure on them and see what result we reach.","start":1471.739,"stop":1478.958,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Now, the economic -- the money and banking professor that I referred to, refers to the appellant's comparison on economic sense as completely absurd and come to the view point of make an asset to asset comparison because he found no real foundation in economic fact to make the great comparison between a deposit in a savings and loans share account, although technically, it's a share of stock and in an equity investment in a share of national bank stock.","start":1478.958,"stop":1522.932,"duration":43.97},{"text":"The -- but essentially, this is our legal argument in regard to substantial competition and in regard to discrimination.","start":1522.932,"stop":1532.945,"duration":10.01},{"text":"I think they have to be considered together and they're considered in reference to the announced purpose of Section 5219 which is to protect national bank investors and the business of national banks from unequal and unfriendly competition.","start":1532.945,"stop":1551.958,"duration":19.01}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But now hasn't Congress done that, required it to be done in a particular way, namely, by limiting the rate of tax on the taxable shares of banks and not more than is levied on like shares of other moneyed capital?","start":1551.958,"stop":1576.875,"duration":24.92}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"And of course the -- the -- this language of Congress has been subject to judicial determine -- judicial interpretation by this Court.","start":1576.875,"stop":1586.639,"duration":9.76},{"text":"And the first thing they had to decide was there any exception to this language?","start":1586.639,"stop":1593.704,"duration":7.07},{"text":"Is it a literal application?","start":1593.704,"stop":1596.101,"duration":2.4},{"text":"And the Court struggled for years in trying to determine what was meant by the phrase, other moneyed capital.","start":1596.101,"stop":1604.583,"duration":8.48},{"text":"But the Court said that it was -- that this statute was not designed to rewrite the tax structures of the State, but as said in the Tradesmen’s case by this Court as late as 1940, it was designed to subject to tax in a practical way, economic equivalence and this is the conclusion that Professor Powell reached in regard to the Section 5219 cases in his law review article, much ado about gross receipts taxes.","start":1604.583,"stop":1645.586,"duration":41},{"text":"That simply -- yes, Section 5219 has been interpreted and if you took the fact that rate was the only thing that you looked at and then you looked at the species of what we might call other moneyed capital, you come out with a mechanical kind of interpretation and discrimination.","start":1645.586,"stop":1667.038,"duration":21.45},{"text":"The difficulty with that argument in the instant case is that it would also bring within the purview of other moneyed capital, bank deposits which would end up with the absurd result of requiring a Michigan state bank to pay a tax of 11.5% or 125 mills on its capital account compared to a 5 1/2 mill tax on the appellant.","start":1667.038,"stop":1697.703,"duration":30.66},{"text":"In other words, if other moneyed capital or moneyed capital within 5219 is so constructed to bring within its purview savings and loan share accounts, it has to bring within its purview United States Government bonds, it has to bring within its purview credit unions and a lot of other favored or differently treated species of property.","start":1697.703,"stop":1726.391,"duration":28.69},{"text":"Now, we simply say that this Court in its wisdom recognized that a mechanical interpretation in the approach of Section 5219 was not adequate.","start":1726.391,"stop":1739.196,"duration":12.8},{"text":"That you had to determine what Congress intended by this provision, what it was trying to protect and then interpret and apply this language in relationship to that intent.","start":1739.196,"stop":1757.785,"duration":18.59},{"text":"And we say that in following -- had -- have I answered your question?","start":1757.785,"stop":1763.231,"duration":5.45},{"text":"In -- in following out this congressional purpose, the -- this Court long recognized that the states could exempt or they could preferentially treat some moneyed capital in the State, without violating any shared tax on national banks by Section 5219, so long as certain essential tests always laid down by this Court to protect an investor in national bank stock was meant.","start":1763.231,"stop":1798.171,"duration":34.94},{"text":"One of them was that it was a partial exemption only.","start":1798.171,"stop":1802.211,"duration":4.04},{"text":"In other words, it was permitting the states for public policy purposes, to carve out some species of property that may be characterized as moneyed capital.","start":1802.211,"stop":1816.032,"duration":13.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Would your (Inaudible) your argument --","start":1816.032,"stop":1818.806,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1818.806,"stop":1819.036,"duration":0.23},{"text":"This is one of the arguments that we have, Your Honor.","start":1819.036,"stop":1821.708,"duration":2.67},{"text":"It is what we call the partial exemption rule, developed by a long number of decisions of this Court, applied by this Court to mutual savings banks, applied by the Sixth Circuit Court of Appeals in the Hoeing case to savings and loan associations.","start":1821.708,"stop":1841.677,"duration":19.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But may I -- I thought that that assumes does it not, that there is a discrimination, what did it justify in order to (Voice Overlap) --","start":1841.677,"stop":1848.8,"duration":7.12}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right.","start":1848.8,"stop":1849.469,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- state policy.","start":1849.469,"stop":1850.269,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- this argument is on the basis that there -- there is a discrimination.","start":1850.269,"stop":1855.99,"duration":5.72},{"text":"We do not concede this in any sense.","start":1855.99,"stop":1858.838,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then, why does that argument apply to it?","start":1858.838,"stop":1862.149,"duration":3.31},{"text":"I thought --","start":1862.149,"stop":1862.378,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"The argument would apply, only Your Honor, if you concluded that the mechanical rate comparison required -- argued by the appellant and -- and questioned by Justice Whittaker, would have to prevail.","start":1862.378,"stop":1878.249,"duration":15.87},{"text":"Then you move on to the question of whether -- even if there is discrimination, still, can the states exempt some moneyed capital?","start":1878.249,"stop":1888.504,"duration":10.25},{"text":"A relatively immaterial part maybe the total moneyed capital employed for just reason, when it's not --","start":1888.504,"stop":1895.67,"duration":7.17}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"No alternative --","start":1895.67,"stop":1896.267,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1896.267,"stop":1896.526,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"-- basis of holding.","start":1896.526,"stop":1897.857,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1897.857,"stop":1898.147,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"It's an alternative (Voice Overlap) --","start":1898.147,"stop":1898.666,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1898.666,"stop":1899.085,"duration":0.42},{"text":"This is another --","start":1899.085,"stop":1899.388,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"You're (Voice Overlap) on both grounds.","start":1899.388,"stop":1900.89,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, they're bow to our -- another arrow to --","start":1900.89,"stop":1904.484,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, your court took your --","start":1904.484,"stop":1905.081,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- our bow.","start":1905.081,"stop":1905.708,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"John M. Harlan II","textObjs":[{"text":"-- your state court, took both grounds.","start":1905.708,"stop":1906.855,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1906.855,"stop":1908.215,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I might -- I might add there that both the trial court and the Supreme Court of Michigan held that the partial exemption rule still obtain.","start":1908.215,"stop":1920.392,"duration":12.18},{"text":"That is that in the instant case, the State of Michigan exempted federal -- federal and state savings and loan associations for a just reason that there wasn't any evidence of any unfriendly discrimination resulting from this kind of treatment, because the two difference -- the differences in the species of property involved and the comparable taxation or economic equivalent.","start":1920.392,"stop":1948.065,"duration":27.67},{"text":"So they said, \"On this basis, we say the appellant has not shown the tax invalid under Section 5219.\"","start":1948.065,"stop":1958.598,"duration":10.53},{"text":"And the Supreme Court also went ahead and decided the mixed question of fact in law that is substantial competition and there found because of the difference is in the institutions, the limited area of real competition that the -- the competition was too narrow and too insubstantial to be considered substantial competition under Section 5219, so this is another bow to our arrow, so to speak.","start":1958.598,"stop":1987.601,"duration":29},{"text":"There is no arrow to our bow, I should say.","start":1987.601,"stop":1992.112,"duration":4.51},{"text":"There is no substantial competition established.","start":1992.112,"stop":1995.703,"duration":3.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree that with reference to the type of competition that your adversary stated making the loan on houses, a building and some property taking more, electing interest insofar as that part shall do business is concerned that the bank have the business that the building and loan associations tried to claim?","start":1995.703,"stop":2021.302,"duration":25.6}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- no, Your Honor, there are differences.","start":2021.302,"stop":2023.614,"duration":2.31},{"text":"Now, it's up to this Court to say whether they are material or not.","start":2023.614,"stop":2028.925,"duration":5.31},{"text":"We certainly are not resting our case essentially on the fact that they are entering the residential mortgage market differently.","start":2028.925,"stop":2038.893,"duration":9.97},{"text":"We do say that the main area of competition is the federally sponsored competition in the F.H.A. and V.A. field and wonder whether this kind of involvement of both institutions would result in a substantial competition prohibited by Congress in another piece of legislation.","start":2038.893,"stop":2061.705,"duration":22.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the core of your argument?","start":2061.705,"stop":2064.186,"duration":2.48},{"text":"The difference in -- is that financial competitive leverage between the national bank and your -- cooperated, your local bank due to the statutory and other advantages that the national banks have by virtue of their charter.","start":2064.186,"stop":2082.166,"duration":17.98}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is one of the keys, definitely.","start":2082.166,"stop":2086.386,"duration":4.22},{"text":"Another key that we have to our argument is simply what --","start":2086.386,"stop":2091.257,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't -- before you go to the other --","start":2091.257,"stop":2092.732,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2092.732,"stop":2094.371,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- isn't, I'll come back to a prior question of mine, isn't that another way of stating that they are better equipped for the competition, not with their -- not competitors.","start":2094.371,"stop":2108.177,"duration":13.81}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is true and so that we have to drop down and try to treat [Attempt to Laughter] them on the basis of what they're able to accomplish because of the different equipment that they have.","start":2108.177,"stop":2123.754,"duration":15.58},{"text":"And this is what the asset for asset or the income to income comparison really tries to do.","start":2123.754,"stop":2130.558,"duration":6.8},{"text":"It tries to get down and measure the result of this different equipment that each institutions have.","start":2130.558,"stop":2136.274,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I -- Could I -- and here you say that the decisions of this Court to which I'm not familiar -- that the decisions of this Court have taken into account the actual fact that this is a big fellow and this is a little fellow and therefore, not -- they're not within the 5209 proscription.","start":2136.274,"stop":2156.704,"duration":20.43}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is true and has taken it into account in various way -- it has taken it into account in saying that only the discriminations resulting on unequal and unfriendly competition is prohibited by Section 5219.","start":2156.704,"stop":2168.897,"duration":12.19}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, -- suppose that the national bank builds up strength in greater power to the accumulation of time and the goodwill, goodwill means the momentum of a going concern and it has more momentum than a little fellow.","start":2168.897,"stop":2184.742,"duration":15.85},{"text":"Would that not come within the condemnation of 5209, if we just -- if your state made a distinction between those -- if it made a quantitative difference?","start":2184.742,"stop":2195.019,"duration":10.28}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is not a quantitative, Your Honor.","start":2195.019,"stop":2196.861,"duration":1.84},{"text":"It is a qualitative.","start":2196.861,"stop":2198.062,"duration":1.2},{"text":"This I want to insist upon.","start":2198.062,"stop":2200.783,"duration":2.72},{"text":"It's the ability of the bank to carry on broad monetary powers.","start":2200.783,"stop":2205.927,"duration":5.14},{"text":"It's the exclusive ability of the bank to receive deposits.","start":2205.927,"stop":2210.278,"duration":4.35},{"text":"Actually, the savings and loan share account is analogous from an economic sense to a bank deposit.","start":2210.278,"stop":2216.079,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Ultimately, you're saying they're not comparable, because ultimately, you're saying (Voice Overlap) --","start":2216.079,"stop":2219.475,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"That ultimately, they're not comparable.","start":2219.475,"stop":2221.886,"duration":2.41},{"text":"Like the appellant said, \"One thing that we say is that how can non-comparable institutions be considered to be in substantial competition within the purview of Section 5219\" or as said by this Court on numerous occasions in regard to the savings bank, \"How can small mutual thrift institutions operating in a narrow field of home financing and collecting thrift savings established by Congress by the Home Owners' Loan Act on the federal level about 1933.\"","start":2221.886,"stop":2257.3,"duration":35.41},{"text":"Life breathes into them by the Treasury of the United States to the -- for home own -- for home own -- the bank board system.\"","start":2257.3,"stop":2266.343,"duration":9.04},{"text":"How can these institutions created for a particular public policy narrow one in thrift savings and home financing and restricted to this purpose, really be very damaging in their operation to a -- a national bank and association.","start":2266.343,"stop":2285.503,"duration":19.16},{"text":"And we simply say, as far as the State is concerned, we're going to look and treat competitive and economic equivalence the same and if we do that, we don't think that we have established an unreasonable or unfriendly competition with the business of national bank or have discouraged people from investing in national bank shares.","start":2285.503,"stop":2310.598,"duration":25.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any question of discrimination between national banks and your state banks in this regard?","start":2310.598,"stop":2317.319,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2317.319,"stop":2318.001,"duration":0.68},{"text":"They are treated -- state banks, national banks and trust companies all three are under the same tax, the 5 1/2-mill tax.","start":2318.001,"stop":2325.036,"duration":7.03},{"text":"Now, state banks pay some of the miscellaneous tax that I referred to and trust companies do that national banks are immune from.","start":2325.036,"stop":2334.006,"duration":8.97},{"text":"And prior to 1952 and prior to this amendment, national banks were -- would escape -- were escaping taxation to the extent of the -- the general tax -- taxes imposed plus this 4 mill corporate franchise privilege thing.","start":2334.006,"stop":2352.281,"duration":18.28}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why are they immune, these national banks?","start":2352.281,"stop":2355.015,"duration":2.73}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2355.015,"stop":2355.452,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why are they immune?","start":2355.452,"stop":2357.008,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the State felt -- the State could not subject them to a corporate privilege tax.","start":2357.008,"stop":2361.81,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words -- in other words, they enjoy a federal immunity, do they not?","start":2361.81,"stop":2365.078,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right, Your Honor.","start":2365.078,"stop":2366.071,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you can't -- can you bind a different qualm of enactment, reach the same dollar and cents result in taxing them in a way in which to be -- for reasons that give them immunity under the federal statutes?","start":2366.071,"stop":2382.533,"duration":16.46}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor --","start":2382.533,"stop":2382.951,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You couldn't do that can you?","start":2382.951,"stop":2384.019,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2384.019,"stop":2384.368,"duration":0.35},{"text":"The -- the --","start":2384.368,"stop":2384.581,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't say they have an advantage which Congress has deem fit to give them that had called it.","start":2384.581,"stop":2391.076,"duration":6.49},{"text":"They -- they're immune from certainly positions of state tax.","start":2391.076,"stop":2393.549,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, right.","start":2393.549,"stop":2394.55,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you can't impose those statutes by some indirection, can you?","start":2394.55,"stop":2397.705,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, Your Honor.","start":2397.705,"stop":2400.007,"duration":2.3},{"text":"We --","start":2400.007,"stop":2400.381,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you -- stating what is remained?","start":2400.381,"stop":2402.44,"duration":2.06},{"text":"I -- I understood you in answer to Justice Frankfurter to say that this Court had held in several cases, the state to carry out a policy to encourage the little (Inaudible) instead of lack of (Inaudible) by making tax rates differ?","start":2402.44,"stop":2422.946,"duration":20.51}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not -- this is -- I -- I'm sorry.","start":2422.946,"stop":2425.357,"duration":2.41},{"text":"The -- the policy I have referred to was what is called the partial exemption rule, Your Honor.","start":2425.357,"stop":2433.45,"duration":8.09},{"text":"We simply mean as stated by this Court on very -- in various decisions cited and quoted at length as shown in our brief, that the State can prefer or exempt tax wise, some other moneyed capital --","start":2433.45,"stop":2451.633,"duration":18.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On what (Voice Overlap) --","start":2451.633,"stop":2451.801,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- without or -- or for just reason and for public policy purposes, for instance, the purpose of trying to foster thrift savings and home ownership under a savings and loan set up.","start":2451.801,"stop":2465.587,"duration":13.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, has that been discussed in connection with fostering smaller institutions rather than large --","start":2465.587,"stop":2472.891,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2472.891,"stop":2473.859,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I misunderstood.","start":2473.859,"stop":2474.678,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this is -- this is not -- had nothing to do with size --","start":2474.678,"stop":2479.579,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I --","start":2479.579,"stop":2480.221,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but -- you mean for an example of it is was part of the first application of the partial exemption rule and the most obvious was the exemption of United States Government bonds in the hands of private individuals.","start":2480.221,"stop":2496.136,"duration":15.91},{"text":"This Court said, \"Well obviously, Congress didn't intend because the states could not tax national bonds in the hands of private bankers or individuals to invalidate a share tax by reference to Section 5219.\"","start":2496.136,"stop":2516.43,"duration":20.29}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Was all the partial exemption tax, it really isn't a reduction in rate, but it's a -- an exemption of things.","start":2516.43,"stop":2528.647,"duration":12.22}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2528.647,"stop":2530.382,"duration":1.74},{"text":"For instance, put it this way, say that -- say that you have within a state, 150 competitive units or of other moneyed capital in competition with the business of banks and say that some of these were held by associations or institutions that the State wanted to favor, say there was five of them.","start":2530.382,"stop":2554.787,"duration":24.4},{"text":"This Court has said, \"This is alright so long as it's for just cause.\"","start":2554.787,"stop":2559.842,"duration":5.06},{"text":"It is partial, it's only 5 out of the 150 and it is not -- does not result in an unfriendly or hostile discrimination against the banks which is the real crux of the meaning of Section 5219.","start":2559.842,"stop":2580.904,"duration":21.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Had your state banks challenge the -- the -- this tax as being discriminatory?","start":2580.904,"stop":2589.873,"duration":8.97}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, Your Honor.","start":2589.873,"stop":2590.844,"duration":0.97},{"text":"In fact --","start":2590.844,"stop":2590.907,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- state banks that --","start":2590.907,"stop":2591.855,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Michigan Bankers Association is solidly behind the State of Michigan in this litigation.","start":2591.855,"stop":2602.679,"duration":10.82},{"text":"Now --","start":2602.679,"stop":2604.086,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who composes that -- that organization?","start":2604.086,"stop":2605.51,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it's -- it's -- now, all of 390 banks in Michigan are also members of that.","start":2605.51,"stop":2610.22,"duration":4.71}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"State banks?","start":2610.22,"stop":2611.39,"duration":1.17},{"text":"Is that --","start":2611.39,"stop":2611.426,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"State and national banks and the Act 9 in the Michigan Public Acts of 1953 hereunder challenged, was drafted by the Taxation Committee of the Michigan Bankers Association and --","start":2611.426,"stop":2626.839,"duration":15.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose of them both?","start":2626.839,"stop":2626.974,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"And – what, both, representing both banks and was placed in the statute for the purpose of bringing financial institutions in Michigan, generally on the same position tax wise and competitive wise.","start":2626.974,"stop":2645.072,"duration":18.1},{"text":"Now, this is referred to at -- at length in our brief, the exact statement of the Bankers Association in regard to their involvement is here.","start":2645.072,"stop":2656.121,"duration":11.05},{"text":"I know the appellant says that he is representing a minority group, that the Bankers Association does not speak for the banks, but are -- certainly are examination of the question, would lead me as an officer of this Court to say that there has been no real concern on the -- behalf of any banks except the appellant over this tax situation.","start":2656.121,"stop":2683.84,"duration":27.72},{"text":"And essentially, that appellant's argument is directed to the competition referred to by the Comptroller over obtaining savings dollars.","start":2683.84,"stop":2695.79,"duration":11.95},{"text":"That the Court in the Hoeing case was not competition, a deposit money, within the purview of Section 5219.","start":2695.79,"stop":2705.803,"duration":10.01},{"text":"I think this Court might, although there is competition in the residential mortgage field, note that Congress is continually involving themselves in making available, more money for residential mortgage purposes and the record in this case shows that up to the appellant's liquidity requirements, they had this need for investment of theirs -- well filled.","start":2705.803,"stop":2738.6,"duration":32.8},{"text":"I'm sure also that the basic reason for Congress in enacting Section 5219, namely to prevent the discouragement of investments in national bank stocks is absent in this case.","start":2738.6,"stop":2757.741,"duration":19.14},{"text":"The appellant is not having any trouble of getting people to buy its stock and has never offered any for sale and it was essentially to protect the stockholder and to protect the national bank in carrying out the monetary functions of the United States Government that this Court handed down the case of McCollough versus Maryland.","start":2757.741,"stop":2782.625,"duration":24.88},{"text":"And it was not to concern itself with economic details of how one institution might buy against another institution where there was no allegation or no attempt to show in any way that the bank's business and its fundamental structure was in any way being impaired.","start":2782.625,"stop":2809.271,"duration":26.65},{"text":"This kind of statement also appears generally in the opinions of this honorable Court.","start":2809.271,"stop":2817.416,"duration":8.14},{"text":"I would like to move to one which may amount to possibly an illuminating part of our position and that is what Congress has actually done in reference to the taxation of these two institutions.","start":2817.416,"stop":2843.47,"duration":26.05},{"text":"Now, the savings and loan associations here in question, the state associations were patterned directly after the federal associations which were created in 1933 by the Congress under the Federal Home Owners' Loan Act.","start":2843.47,"stop":2864.05,"duration":20.58},{"text":"And in that legislation, Congress spelled out the purpose of that -- of the creation of the federal Home Owners' Loan -- creation of the federal savings and loan institutions under this statute and it there said that such associations shall loan their funds only on the security of their shares or the security of first liens upon homes or combinations of homes.","start":2864.05,"stop":2897.274,"duration":33.22}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't quite hear you.","start":2897.274,"stop":2898.33,"duration":1.06},{"text":"Could you refer me to where that is in your brief?","start":2898.33,"stop":2899.729,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is page 15, Your Honor.","start":2899.729,"stop":2901.642,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Of your brief?","start":2901.642,"stop":2902.72,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, of our brief.","start":2902.72,"stop":2903.887,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Main brief.","start":2903.887,"stop":2904.659,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Main brief, yes, Your Honor.","start":2904.659,"stop":2905.817,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":2905.817,"stop":2906.311,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we have only one.[Attempt to Laughter]","start":2906.311,"stop":2910.113,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought you had a reply brief.","start":2910.113,"stop":2911.359,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, Your Honor.","start":2911.359,"stop":2912.248,"duration":0.89},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) We have --","start":2912.248,"stop":2913.238,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Flip the other side.","start":2913.238,"stop":2914.024,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I will apologize for its size, but there's only one.","start":2914.024,"stop":2916.982,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's alright.","start":2916.982,"stop":2920.671,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"We're on pages 15 and 16,.","start":2920.671,"stop":2922.685,"duration":2.01},{"text":"Congress spells out generally, what they have done in reference to the creation of federal savings and loan associations.","start":2922.685,"stop":2929.942,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Now, the state associations in question are patterned identically after these federal associations and our statutory analysis in our brief will indicate that.","start":2929.942,"stop":2945.343,"duration":15.4},{"text":"But then on page 17 of our brief, Congress made it abundantly clear what it was going to require of the states in reference to the taxation of these mutual thrift institutions.","start":2945.343,"stop":2962.109,"duration":16.77},{"text":"It there said, \"No state territorial county, municipal or local taxing authority shall impose any tax on such associations or their franchise capital reserve surplus loans or income greater than that imposed by such authority on other similar, local, mutual or cooperative thrift in home financing institutions.\"","start":2962.109,"stop":2988.456,"duration":26.35},{"text":"Now, we maintain that Congress in -- in 1933, contrary to the appellant's contention, set forth the purpose of these institutions and told the states what norm to use in taxing them.","start":2988.456,"stop":3008.007,"duration":19.55},{"text":"Now we simply assert that this is in pari materia legislation, it must be read in conjunction with Section 5219 and that the states only have to concern themselves in taxing mutual institutions like this, with similar mutual institutions and not with what is done with national banks.","start":3008.007,"stop":3030.93,"duration":22.92},{"text":"Now, it's interesting to know what Congress did in reference to providing for the taxation of both the joint land banks and the national agricultural credit associations.","start":3030.93,"stop":3048.279,"duration":17.35},{"text":"The taxation provisions were relative to -- those two associations is set out on page 159 of the brief.","start":3048.279,"stop":3057.358,"duration":9.08},{"text":"Now, there, Congress tied in to 5219 and to the taxation of national bank stocks, the taxation of the stock of joint-stock land banks and the stock of National Agricultural Credit Corporations.","start":3057.358,"stop":3076.65,"duration":19.29},{"text":"In other words, a stock-type institution operating in the financial field created by Congress was tied into 5219 language and test, while a mutual institution such as the savings and loan association was -- was related to an entirely different kind of test.","start":3076.65,"stop":3106.43,"duration":29.78},{"text":"In the treatment of the savings and loan associations under the federal income tax law, which has been a subject by the way, of much controversy between banks and savings and loan associations, Congress saw fit to treat and classify these two institutions decidedly different.","start":3106.43,"stop":3131.372,"duration":24.94},{"text":"In reference to the savings and loan associations, they created a bad debt reserve of 12% of the income of these institutions and also permitted the institutions to deduct their dividends to their shareholders in the same way as banks were permitted to deduct the interest paid to their depositors.","start":3131.372,"stop":3164.313,"duration":32.94},{"text":"Also, Congress, when it created the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation and insured people who placed their moneys on deposit in banks against laws, also saw fit to treat by analogy, an investment or a deposit in a savings and loan share account and this was done by the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation.","start":3164.313,"stop":3192.546,"duration":28.23},{"text":"Congress again treat in this mutual fund of a savings and loan association that has no equity capital and has not stock, the equivalent with the bank deposit which is the kind of equation the State believes to be equitable and fair in this cause.","start":3192.546,"stop":3214.209,"duration":21.66},{"text":"Also, Congress, in legislating in the District of Columbia, according to the appellant's theory of equality, is now discriminating 3 to 1 against the gross income of national banking institutions in the district.","start":3214.209,"stop":3237.914,"duration":23.71},{"text":"And in 1923, this Statute, Section 5219 was amended by the Congress and considered in detail after this Court's decision in the Richmond case in 256 U.S. and the congressional record there shows that Congress was well aware of this Court's treatment of mutual savings banks and other mutual institutions as being without the purview of Section 5219.","start":3237.914,"stop":3272.046,"duration":34.13},{"text":"And that also, this Court was well aware of the fact that this Court had concluded in the Clement National Bank case that bank deposits were not within the protection of Section 5219.","start":3272.046,"stop":3287.874,"duration":15.83},{"text":"And thus, in the 1923 Amendment, Congress again by not making any provision to overrule the judicial pronouncement of this Court, again made it manifest and abundantly clear that they were not going to compare a savings and loan share account with a -- with a share of national bank stock for Section 5219 purposes.","start":3287.874,"stop":3314.19,"duration":26.32},{"text":"Admittedly, as appellant says, it is a share of stock, but a \"tree\" is also a tree.","start":3314.19,"stop":3326.712,"duration":12.52},{"text":"In the instant case, there's no equity that a person can possibly obtain by placing a dollar with a savings and loan share account.","start":3326.712,"stop":3337.384,"duration":10.67},{"text":"These savings and loan associations stand ready and open to accept other depositors on the same level, on the same basis as their existing depositors.","start":3337.384,"stop":3349.438,"duration":12.05},{"text":"If a person withdraws the money, only thing that they can withdraw under the federal statute and the Michigan statute is the dollar that they put in plus dividends paid out of current earnings.","start":3349.438,"stop":3362.708,"duration":13.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Aren't you proving a little too much?","start":3362.708,"stop":3365.395,"duration":2.69},{"text":"What you're now -- and if I followed your argument, you now say, \"These are, as a matter of categories, different institutions in the savings and loan institutions is but from its very nature outside of the restrictive provisions of 5219?\"","start":3365.395,"stop":3383.946,"duration":18.55},{"text":"Isn't that what you are saying?","start":3383.946,"stop":3384.675,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right, Your Honor and we have said that this Court has so stated and we are saying that Congress has treated the two institutions traditionally different and that now, we're trying to bring together mechanically, by a mechanical interpretation of 5219 under the Hartford case ignoring 100 years of history in legislation of this Court.","start":3384.675,"stop":3413.552,"duration":28.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The fact that Congress by legislation has treated them differently, doesn't mean that the State of Michigan or any other state can treat them different, does it?","start":3413.552,"stop":3422.731,"duration":9.18}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, but we say that it manifest a congressional intent not because -- remember, we have here two federal institutions.","start":3422.731,"stop":3432.097,"duration":9.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You say in effect, that the body of this -- this continuing body of legislation treating national banks in the conventional form and savings loan institutions so far as Congress can deal with it in the districts, as so consistently in a body of enactment, treated them differently that as a matter of law, one is to infer that 5219 impliedly represents that same by implication, that same differentiation.","start":3432.097,"stop":3459.869,"duration":27.77}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"This is right, Your Honor.","start":3459.869,"stop":3462.09,"duration":2.22},{"text":"I mean, in other words, we see a consistent pattern of decisions of this Court ruling out mutual savings bank, savings deposit, savings and loan association up to the Hoeing case, up to the Shreveport case of this Court of 1933, up to the Tradesmens case by this Court in 1940, we -- and we see paralleling that a congressional enactment that would support it.","start":3462.09,"stop":3488.207,"duration":26.12},{"text":"And essentially then, we are saying that -- that Congress has made it clear that they do not consider a mutual institution such as they created under the Home Owners' Loan Act of 1933, comparable to a -- a savings and loan -- comparable to a national bank capital, which is protected by 5219.","start":3488.207,"stop":3514.331,"duration":26.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Dexter, I understood Mr. Klein, in his argument concerning the earlier cases to say that the character of building and loan associations had -- had changed completely in recent years and that therefore, the earlier cases do not apply, would you mind addressing yourself to that?","start":3514.331,"stop":3536.827,"duration":22.5}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, I would very much like to comment on that.","start":3536.827,"stop":3540.843,"duration":4.02},{"text":"Number one, the associations that I have just referred to in regard to public policy, were created in 1933 by Congress and so, his assertion that there's no public policy reason for distinct treatment of these institutions is rather belied by what Congress actually did in 1933 and what kind of institution that they said they were creating under the General Welfare Clause.","start":3540.843,"stop":3571.112,"duration":30.27},{"text":"And also, the testimony in this cause clearly indicates that the changes that he is talking about are changes of form without substance that the -- essence of their mutuality is that they have no stock.","start":3571.112,"stop":3587.067,"duration":15.95},{"text":"There are a mutual concern corporation or a mutual body and that it is a vehicle created expressly by Congress and for the states for the purpose of promoting thrift savings and home ownership and there has not been in the record of this cause that would lead anyone to assume that an established public policy of 100 years should now be set aside.","start":3587.067,"stop":3614.561,"duration":27.49},{"text":"And I should say in this connection that there are -- were several cases in the -- in this Court involving the status of mutual savings bank under 5219 and each time the bank came before this Court, they argued that now, we have a -- institution different in character, different in scope than -- that of the other institutions that the Court ruled upon in the prior decisions.","start":3614.561,"stop":3647.623,"duration":33.06},{"text":"Now, I might say in closing that there is one aspect of the whole area that the appellant has failed to note, in terms of trying to possibly bring Section 5219 up to date and that is that in 1864 when the statute we're talking about was first enacted, banks' capital -- equity capital amounted to 60% of their employable assets.","start":3647.623,"stop":3675.415,"duration":27.79},{"text":"In 1919 and around the time of the Mercantile case --","start":3675.415,"stop":3680.034,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you may finish that statement (Voice Overlap)","start":3680.034,"stop":3681.403,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"William David Dexter","textObjs":[{"text":"In 1919 at the time of the Mercantile case, the ratio was 40 to 60 and in 1952, the capital of the bank were now talking to has a ratio of 4% to the total employable assets of that institution.","start":3681.403,"stop":3703.938,"duration":22.54},{"text":"I thank you very much.","start":3703.938,"stop":3705.984,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Klein.","start":3705.984,"stop":3707.843,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Victor W. Klein","textObjs":[{"text":"Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3707.843,"stop":3710.859,"duration":3.02},{"text":"Within the limited few minutes I have left, I'll endeavor to answer two or three basic errors in the argument.","start":3710.859,"stop":3719.33,"duration":8.47},{"text":"The basic error of appellee's argument and of Professor Woodward is the appellee does not like R.S. 5219, which is a tax on shares of national banks and he only wants the comparison made not with other moneyed capital in any form, but only with institutions which have the power to take deposits and to do a general banking business, because there is no business whatsoever which may take deposits except a bank.","start":3719.33,"stop":3770.975,"duration":51.64},{"text":"This Court has held that other moneyed capital is not limited to banking institutions or the institutions which may take deposits, you've said it in Richmond, you've said it in Hartford and you've said it in Minnesota.","start":3770.975,"stop":3791.355,"duration":20.38},{"text":"And Congress, on several occasions, was asked to change the law to limit it to other banks and refused to change it.","start":3791.355,"stop":3803.138,"duration":11.78},{"text":"This is a tax on shares and not on all of the assets of the institution.","start":3803.138,"stop":3813.495,"duration":10.36},{"text":"The same argument advanced by appellee was advanced by the State of Minnesota in the Minnesota case where they too said, \"Banks can do business on deposits forgetting that they had to pay those deposits, they're liabilities\" and said, \"Compare the tax burden not on shares or total assets deducting the deposit liability.\"","start":3813.495,"stop":3840.179,"duration":26.68},{"text":"The State of Minnesota made the same argument, but this Court said, \"Oh, no, this is a share tax.","start":3840.179,"stop":3847.213,"duration":7.03},{"text":"You must compare the net assets after deducting liability or the capital stock.\"","start":3847.213,"stop":3854.597,"duration":7.38},{"text":"Moneyed capital therefore, can mean the investment of an individual who may not take deposits and the investment of any business, which may not take deposits.","start":3854.597,"stop":3869.755,"duration":15.16},{"text":"And I submit the Shreveport case, sustains our position because that case was raised on two questions and that followed Hartford shortly.","start":3869.755,"stop":3882.337,"duration":12.58},{"text":"Number one, the State -- the bank attacked it on the Fourteenth Amendment that savings and loan were not like banks.","start":3882.337,"stop":3891.121,"duration":8.78},{"text":"On the Fourteenth Amendment, there was a reasonable classification, but on the second ground of attack that it violated this revised statute, the national bank tax act, the Court did not say it was of a different character and couldn't come under R.S. 5219, no.","start":3891.121,"stop":3913.831,"duration":22.71},{"text":"Mr. Justice Brandeis went into the question and said, \"There was no competition in fact, the banks weren't competing or the savings and loan weren't competing with the banks.\"","start":3913.831,"stop":3927.492,"duration":13.66},{"text":"He wouldn't have discussed that had he held that there were such different comparable character that they couldn't as a matter of law, compete with one another.","start":3927.492,"stop":3939.127,"duration":11.63},{"text":"Now, on the proposition, Mr. Justice Frankfurter said, \"Little fellow versus big fellow.\"","start":3939.127,"stop":3947.336,"duration":8.21},{"text":"In this instance, there are 67 savings and loan associations and 77 national banks in Michigan and if you check the chart on page 17, you will see that those 67 savings and loan associations did a far greater residential mortgage business, then the 77 national banks, including appellant.","start":3947.336,"stop":3972.736,"duration":25.4},{"text":"And if Your Honors would be good enough to see what has happened on page 81 of our brief, the growth of these savings and loan associations since the change in character in 1935, has been phenomenal both in Michigan, it has gone up from 1940, from a $116,000,000 to $537,000,000, till today, it's over $1,200,000,000 and nationally, the growth has gone from $5,000,000,000 in 1940 to $63,000,000,000.","start":3972.736,"stop":4013.47,"duration":40.73},{"text":"So, these aren't little institutions which are helpless.","start":4013.47,"stop":4017.706,"duration":4.24},{"text":"They have had a phenomenal growth and their in the mortgage business has been at least three times greater than the growth of national banks.","start":4017.706,"stop":4027.353,"duration":9.65},{"text":"Now, this reference to Mr. Chief Justice about state banks complaining or other banks.","start":4027.353,"stop":4036.079,"duration":8.73},{"text":"The Michigan Banker's Association as an association did not take that position.","start":4036.079,"stop":4042.812,"duration":6.73},{"text":"It was a three or four-man committee.","start":4042.812,"stop":4046.268,"duration":3.46},{"text":"They were asked later when it came to our attention to submit it to the membership for a vote.","start":4046.268,"stop":4053.072,"duration":6.8},{"text":"They refused to do so.","start":4053.072,"stop":4055.77,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Sixty odd banks including state banks sir, attempted to file a brief amicus in this Court, protesting the position taken by this tax committee.","start":4055.77,"stop":4068.824,"duration":13.05},{"text":"And this tax committee on the proof of this Attorney General went to the state legislature because -- not because they thought this tax was a valid tax, they didn't want a state income tax and they preferred this to a state income tax and said, \"We will assist the State to defend this tax, this tax of doubtful validity, if its validity is attacked by a national bank\" and they certainly cannot bargain away the rights given to Congress.","start":4068.824,"stop":4107.622,"duration":38.8},{"text":"The small tax committee has no power to bargain away our rights under the law and rights of other national banks.","start":4107.622,"stop":4116.439,"duration":8.82},{"text":"Thank you.","start":4116.439,"stop":4154.667,"duration":38.23}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Jan  18 - 19, 1961","petitioner":"","respondent":"","docket":"155","citation":"365 US 467 (1961)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/365/467","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Mar 6, 1961"}